{"answer": "The knowledge suggests the crossover depends on task specificity and data availability. Fine-tuned 7B models outperform few-shot 175B on domain-specific tasks, indicating the threshold is task complexity — not model size. LoRA achieves this with 10-100x fewer parameters at ranks 4-64, making fine-tuning increasingly cost-effective. RAG shifts the threshold further by compensating for model size limitations: reducing hallucination from 15-30% to under 5% means a smaller fine-tuned model with retrieval may match a larger few-shot model. The evidence points to a complexity threshold around tasks requiring deep domain vocabulary and structured reasoning, where few-shot prompting cannot substitute for parameter specialization."}